WEBVTT

00:14.098 --> 00:16.517
(bell tolling)

00:25.568 --> 00:27.570
♪ ♪

00:29.405 --> 00:31.824
(man screaming)

00:31.866 --> 00:34.368
(bones crunching)

00:39.999 --> 00:42.376
(clanking, crunching)

01:00.895 --> 01:04.231
(crunching continues)

01:26.378 --> 01:28.589
♪ ♪

01:52.613 --> 01:54.615
♪ ♪

02:01.705 --> 02:04.291
KRISTOFF: To understand
the Orloj and her curse,

02:04.333 --> 02:08.212
you must understand Prague.

02:08.254 --> 02:10.965
The greatest clock in the world

02:11.006 --> 02:14.134
constructed for
the greatest city in the world.

02:14.176 --> 02:17.721
And like any precious jewel,

02:17.763 --> 02:20.891
she was jealously protected.

02:20.933 --> 02:26.146
Once the clock stopped,
the city stopped.

02:26.188 --> 02:29.191
The future of Prague
was cursed.

02:31.235 --> 02:33.779
(horse sputters)

02:48.961 --> 02:51.005
JAN:
Dirvick.

02:53.132 --> 02:54.758
Stop it.

02:54.800 --> 02:56.176
It is just a mask.

02:56.218 --> 02:57.970
I know.

02:58.012 --> 02:59.805
I thought Prague was clear
of the plague.

02:59.847 --> 03:02.933
Brother,
think instead of clocks.

03:02.975 --> 03:04.226
(laughs):
Clocks.

03:14.278 --> 03:15.613
Yes.

03:19.491 --> 03:21.827
It's a marvel.

03:21.869 --> 03:25.289
It may as well be a statue.

03:25.331 --> 03:26.707
And it will put money
in our pockets.

03:26.749 --> 03:28.709
(laughs)

03:30.169 --> 03:31.211
(gasps)

03:39.011 --> 03:42.222
Can we help you, death-man?

03:46.101 --> 03:48.979
I am Dr. Kristoff Brehovy,

03:49.021 --> 03:52.775
and I'm looking for
Jan and Dirvick Mirandesh.

03:52.816 --> 03:55.486
Unless they are your masters?

03:58.030 --> 04:00.950
Sir, we are the men you seek.

04:00.991 --> 04:03.410
You look like Turks.

04:03.452 --> 04:04.787
Uh...

04:04.828 --> 04:06.664
We have no country.

04:06.705 --> 04:10.167
And no plague.
So keep your distance.

04:10.209 --> 04:12.962
But your letter says
Jan and Dirvick of Bohemia.

04:13.003 --> 04:16.173
You mean our letter
to the mayor?

04:16.215 --> 04:17.758
Yeah, God rest his soul.

04:17.800 --> 04:21.929
The foul plague,
that is the reason I am here.

04:21.971 --> 04:25.140
But it does not explain
why you are here.

04:25.182 --> 04:27.935
-It is where we live now.
-(flies buzzing)

04:27.977 --> 04:30.854
And those are good names for
where we live, yes?

04:30.896 --> 04:33.607
(quietly):
Dirvick.

04:33.649 --> 04:35.234
Don't mind him.

04:35.275 --> 04:39.613
I'm sorry, are there any
clockmakers here?

04:39.655 --> 04:41.240
We can be on our way.

04:41.281 --> 04:43.534
No, no, no, no.
No, I, uh, I apologize.

04:43.575 --> 04:46.120
Welcome to Prague.

04:46.161 --> 04:48.831
And to your new home.

04:52.418 --> 04:53.627
Come.

04:59.341 --> 05:00.759
Come.

05:12.354 --> 05:14.356
Oh.

05:14.398 --> 05:15.941
(gasps)

05:18.986 --> 05:20.738
(laughs softly)

05:20.779 --> 05:24.158
You'll have to forgive
my brother, he's a...

05:24.199 --> 05:25.868
a bit enthusiastic.

05:25.909 --> 05:30.831
It shows me that my faith in
your expertise is well-placed.

05:30.873 --> 05:33.459
JAN:
Well, more his than mine.

05:33.500 --> 05:35.794
My skill lies more
in the care and feeding

05:35.836 --> 05:37.629
of Dirvick's enthusiasms.

05:37.671 --> 05:41.050
To your benefit, of course.

05:41.091 --> 05:44.136
Ah, it's a wonder.

05:44.178 --> 05:48.974
KRISTOFF: This clock has
remained silent for 60 years.

05:49.016 --> 05:53.103
Now, if your brother can
make the hands move

05:53.145 --> 05:55.105
and the bell toll again...

05:55.147 --> 05:58.233
-Well, as long as
our price is agreeable...
-Yes.

05:58.275 --> 06:01.695
...you don't have to take
another step in here ever again.

06:01.737 --> 06:07.493
Oh. Many men like you have
tried, and many have failed.

06:07.534 --> 06:09.703
Uh, master clockmaker...

06:09.745 --> 06:12.206
Master?

06:12.247 --> 06:15.292
Oh, I am no master,

06:15.334 --> 06:17.669
merely a journeyman

06:17.711 --> 06:20.672
seeking to prove
his capabilities. (chuckles)

06:20.714 --> 06:24.927
Eh, what Dirvick means is that
in the shadow of the Orloj,

06:24.968 --> 06:29.389
no clockmaker could
consider himself a master,

06:29.431 --> 06:33.060
unless he first masters
this machine.

06:33.102 --> 06:35.479
It's not merely
one machine, brother.

06:35.521 --> 06:37.648
-Hmm?
-These are many.

06:37.689 --> 06:40.317
Clocks within clocks,
each driving the others.

06:40.359 --> 06:42.736
And the complication
of the clocks themselves...

06:42.778 --> 06:46.156
These, too, individual machines,

06:46.198 --> 06:49.159
built with a single purpose,

06:49.201 --> 06:54.998
but operating in concert
with the whole.

06:55.040 --> 06:59.253
-It moves, Jan.
-Or will, when we're done.

07:03.423 --> 07:06.969
Kristoff has, uh,
made a generous offer...

07:08.887 --> 07:11.849
I would fix it for pleasure.

07:11.890 --> 07:15.018
As you can see,

07:15.060 --> 07:19.481
my brother has his function,
and I have mine.

07:19.523 --> 07:24.319
I-If there's anything else you
need, please send for me.

07:24.361 --> 07:29.324
Well, um, this job is bigger
than any one man or two men,

07:29.366 --> 07:31.743
no matter how en-enthusiastic.

07:31.785 --> 07:34.163
The foreman will join you
tomorrow.

07:34.204 --> 07:36.540
-Just the foreman?
-No, no, no.

07:36.582 --> 07:39.710
He-He'll bring whatever men
he decides are suitable.

07:39.751 --> 07:42.796
-Good evening.
-Good evening.

07:46.383 --> 07:47.968
Fix it for the pleasure?

07:50.095 --> 07:52.097
♪ ♪

07:55.934 --> 07:57.895
(tongue clicking rhythmically)

08:10.908 --> 08:12.743
Hello?

08:27.883 --> 08:29.176
Um...

08:34.473 --> 08:36.391
Aah!

08:36.433 --> 08:38.518
(groaning)

08:43.941 --> 08:45.275
JAN:
Dirvick?

08:45.317 --> 08:48.487
-Master!
-(Dirvick groaning)

08:48.528 --> 08:49.738
Look what I brought.

08:49.780 --> 08:52.449
-Did you see it?
-What?

08:52.491 --> 08:54.326
Some of the gears moved.

08:54.368 --> 08:55.911
Impossible.

08:55.953 --> 08:58.705
Nothing has moved in this clock
over 60 years.

09:00.499 --> 09:05.045
Mm. Come.
What happened to your hand?

09:05.087 --> 09:07.172
Here...

09:07.214 --> 09:09.925
take it.

09:09.967 --> 09:12.219
Ow.

09:12.261 --> 09:13.929
(laughs):
You were meant to drink that.

09:16.556 --> 09:19.977
Fix yourself, clockmaker.

09:20.018 --> 09:22.479
(Dirvick panting)

09:29.945 --> 09:33.448
The Orloj is our home.

09:33.490 --> 09:36.326
And the only good one
in some time.

09:36.368 --> 09:41.540
In your letter,
you lied to them, didn't you?

09:41.581 --> 09:44.501
You said
I'm a master clockmaker.

09:46.878 --> 09:50.549
What would you have me say? Hmm?

09:50.590 --> 09:53.844
My brother has grand ambitions.

09:53.885 --> 09:56.805
Please pay him as though
he has already received

09:56.847 --> 09:58.307
his hoped-for recognition.

09:58.348 --> 10:01.560
I am who I am.
I am not ashamed.

10:01.601 --> 10:04.146
You should not be ashamed.

10:04.187 --> 10:07.607
But we should not
go hungry, either. Hmm?

10:11.028 --> 10:15.615
Worry more about your hand than
your reputation as an artisan.

10:19.953 --> 10:23.248
If it gets worse, I'll send
for the surgeon in the morning.

10:23.290 --> 10:26.126
Hmm? Now, hold still.

10:26.168 --> 10:28.837
(Dirvick hisses)

10:31.298 --> 10:33.675
-(chuckles)
-Ow.

10:36.261 --> 10:39.639
I'm more worried
about the clock.

10:39.681 --> 10:43.310
There are no plans.

10:43.352 --> 10:48.607
Who builds a wonder like this
and leaves no plans behind?

10:48.648 --> 10:51.693
JAN: Someone very confident
or very stupid.

10:55.655 --> 10:58.408
(kisses)

10:58.450 --> 11:01.161
It's madness.

11:01.203 --> 11:04.623
There is a little madness
in every genius, brother.

11:04.664 --> 11:09.336
Now, sleep.
Plans are for daylight.

11:09.378 --> 11:11.963
(grunts)

11:26.686 --> 11:29.356
(laughter, indistinct chatter)

11:33.360 --> 11:35.320
You are the foreman?

11:35.362 --> 11:37.781
We were promised a full crew.

11:37.823 --> 11:39.491
We're paying for double the men.

11:39.533 --> 11:41.535
You're paying double for these.

11:41.576 --> 11:43.662
Ridiculous.

11:43.703 --> 11:45.288
What is ridiculous
is that I managed

11:45.330 --> 11:47.457
to convince these men
to enter the cursed clock.

11:47.499 --> 11:49.835
You're not the first
to come here with plans

11:49.876 --> 11:51.169
to restore the Orloj.

11:51.211 --> 11:53.922
Superstitions and fairy tales.

11:53.964 --> 11:57.092
No, death and nightmares.

11:57.134 --> 12:00.512
They all went mad, my friend.

12:00.554 --> 12:05.016
And those that stayed
too long... died.

12:05.058 --> 12:08.478
The city has suffered
since then, pestilence run amok.

12:08.520 --> 12:12.858
Well, you've seen the fires,
the masks?

12:15.735 --> 12:17.320
The shell of what Prague was

12:17.362 --> 12:19.281
and they say
it's because the clock

12:19.322 --> 12:20.949
doesn't want to be restored.

12:20.991 --> 12:25.245
If all of that is true,
what are you doing here?

12:25.287 --> 12:28.206
Well, you're paying double.

12:28.248 --> 12:30.417
And I'm hungry.

12:30.459 --> 12:32.878
(flies buzzing)

12:33.920 --> 12:36.298
(horse whinnies)

12:36.339 --> 12:38.341
(indistinct chatter)

12:46.766 --> 12:49.227
There are no such things
as curses.

12:52.856 --> 12:54.858
(indistinct chatter)

12:56.693 --> 12:58.820
MAN:
There you go.

12:58.862 --> 13:02.073
-Now, you pass that one down.
-Got it.

13:02.115 --> 13:05.118
(indistinct chatter continues)

13:10.540 --> 13:12.542
MAN:
All right, there it is.

13:12.584 --> 13:14.753
There it is.

13:14.794 --> 13:16.630
FOREMAN:
And this isn't the only assembly

13:16.671 --> 13:18.757
we've found in such a state.

13:18.798 --> 13:20.342
I just don't understand
how something

13:20.383 --> 13:21.843
like this could happen.

13:21.885 --> 13:23.595
It didn't.

13:23.637 --> 13:26.765
It... it was deliberate.

13:26.806 --> 13:30.769
As I said, the clock doesn't
want to be restored.

13:30.810 --> 13:33.772
(chuckles)
Or someone doesn't.

13:33.813 --> 13:35.524
That's certain.

13:35.565 --> 13:37.817
Show me the rest.

13:42.739 --> 13:45.116
(tongue clicking rhythmically)

13:55.669 --> 13:56.920
Ah...

14:07.639 --> 14:09.474
(continues clicking tongue)

14:36.501 --> 14:38.044
(pants)

15:00.525 --> 15:04.112
(yelling)

15:05.614 --> 15:09.909
Take a hammer to it
or pray to the Lord.

15:09.951 --> 15:11.494
-(men shouting)
-We have to stop it

15:11.536 --> 15:12.871
before it kills your brother.

15:12.912 --> 15:15.206
Whatever makes it stop.

15:20.920 --> 15:23.423
(screaming)

15:31.514 --> 15:33.391
(men shouting)

15:48.990 --> 15:52.661
KRISTOFF: The Orloj is many
clocks within one clock,

15:52.702 --> 15:56.873
all turning in perfect
synchronization.

15:56.915 --> 16:00.919
It was Master Clockmaker
Hanus Carolinum

16:00.960 --> 16:03.672
who breathed life
into this clock's unique

16:03.713 --> 16:05.924
astrological functions.

16:05.965 --> 16:08.551
Some people believe
there was a deeper purpose,

16:08.593 --> 16:11.596
to give her the power
to forecast the fates

16:11.638 --> 16:13.765
of kings and countries.

16:13.807 --> 16:16.893
The Orloj told
not just the time.

16:16.935 --> 16:20.438
The Orloj told the future.

16:22.482 --> 16:24.776
JAN:
The clock moved on its own.

16:24.818 --> 16:27.821
And what really matters
is what they believe.

16:27.862 --> 16:30.448
And they believe in the curse.

16:30.490 --> 16:32.742
I'm sorry.
I'll collect my brother

16:32.784 --> 16:36.621
and ask only payment
for time and expenses.

16:36.663 --> 16:38.707
Stay. They'll pay you double.

16:38.748 --> 16:40.375
Now who's mad?

16:40.417 --> 16:42.544
Two men doing the job of 20.

16:42.585 --> 16:44.879
We'll find you men
who are not afraid of stories.

16:44.921 --> 16:49.509
There are curses and there are
those who are being cursed.

16:49.551 --> 16:54.139
There's only one
cure for both: hope.

16:54.180 --> 16:59.102
-Double, you said?
-Yes, double.

16:59.144 --> 17:01.438
-Okay.
-Good.

17:29.090 --> 17:31.509
♪ ♪

17:40.226 --> 17:42.228
(ethereal singing)

18:03.166 --> 18:05.376
(gears clanking)

18:07.295 --> 18:09.297
Brother?

18:11.633 --> 18:15.011
I have been back and forth
across the city

18:15.053 --> 18:19.015
and return
with excellent news...

18:19.057 --> 18:21.059
and news somewhat
less than excellent.

18:21.100 --> 18:25.438
All right, so... (chuckles)
none of the news is good.

18:25.480 --> 18:30.610
No. No. Unless you're you.

18:30.652 --> 18:33.363
Because you're
the one who offered

18:33.404 --> 18:34.906
to fix this monstrosity...

18:34.948 --> 18:38.368
(chuckles)
for the pleasure.

18:38.409 --> 18:40.829
Your pleasure.

18:43.206 --> 18:45.875
Oh.

18:45.917 --> 18:51.589
All right. Not quite that bad.

18:51.631 --> 18:54.092
They doubled our pay.

18:54.133 --> 18:57.470
Thank you. My pleasure.

18:57.512 --> 18:59.848
Yes.

18:59.889 --> 19:02.141
Oh, my pleasure.

19:06.396 --> 19:11.317
And... (chuckles) we don't
have to share it with a soul.

19:11.359 --> 19:12.986
(laughs) Nope.

19:13.027 --> 19:16.114
Nope, because we are on our own.

19:16.155 --> 19:20.368
Again.

19:20.410 --> 19:22.871
No crew.

19:22.912 --> 19:25.874
Social animal that you are,

19:25.915 --> 19:28.668
I am sure you weep
at the very thought.

19:28.710 --> 19:32.213
Huh? Where are you?

19:32.255 --> 19:34.173
I'm sorry. I'm sorry.

19:44.851 --> 19:48.187
Hey, you. You.

19:48.229 --> 19:51.190
What are you staring at? Huh?

19:51.232 --> 19:54.527
This? (laughs)

19:54.569 --> 19:56.362
How dare you to judge me

19:56.404 --> 19:59.574
when your Lord and Savior
made endless supply

19:59.616 --> 20:01.034
out of water in Canaan.

20:04.829 --> 20:06.581
(liquid splashes)

20:09.459 --> 20:11.461
Dirvick?

20:20.970 --> 20:24.849
Brother.

20:24.891 --> 20:28.478
It's a cursed city.

20:28.519 --> 20:32.023
I saw things, horrible things.

20:32.065 --> 20:34.567
Show me your hand.

20:35.944 --> 20:38.488
-You should have come to me.
-Soldiers, brother.

20:38.529 --> 20:41.366
Women and children
under the sword, and worse.

20:44.327 --> 20:47.080
Flame consuming
nearly every building.

20:47.121 --> 20:51.250
Great, black buzzing birds
raining death from the skies.

20:51.292 --> 20:54.629
Eyes on fire.

20:54.671 --> 20:56.631
Clockwork monsters
on wheels and tracks,

20:56.673 --> 20:59.133
rolling through
the streets of Prague.

20:59.175 --> 21:01.719
Quiet. Rest your mind.

21:01.761 --> 21:05.431
We need to find you
a surgeon tonight.

21:05.473 --> 21:08.393
DIRVICK:
It showed me all of it.

21:10.603 --> 21:12.021
It cursed them with it.

21:14.732 --> 21:16.609
I can stop it.

21:16.651 --> 21:19.237
I can fix the clock.

21:19.278 --> 21:21.030
Dirvick, enough.

21:21.072 --> 21:23.199
I have this.

21:23.241 --> 21:26.536
You see?

21:26.577 --> 21:29.872
I found this.

21:29.914 --> 21:34.002
It's the key to unlock
the missing piece.

21:34.043 --> 21:36.546
Enough, I said.

21:36.587 --> 21:39.549
You could lose your entire arm.

21:39.590 --> 21:42.969
Is that what you want? Huh?

21:43.011 --> 21:45.430
We are leaving now.

21:47.140 --> 21:49.392
Dirvick.

21:49.434 --> 21:52.770
-Dirvick.
-No.

21:52.812 --> 21:56.274
Dirvick, stop it.
Dirvick, stop it.

21:56.315 --> 21:58.234
-Please!
-(growling): No!

21:58.276 --> 21:59.444
Dirvick.

21:59.485 --> 22:01.654
Dirvick, stop!

22:13.916 --> 22:16.669
(coughs)

22:29.265 --> 22:31.225
(panting)

22:39.776 --> 22:41.778
♪ ♪

22:45.698 --> 22:47.241
(flies buzzing)

22:58.461 --> 23:01.714
What your brother suffers from
is neither the plague,

23:01.756 --> 23:05.635
nor any contagion
I can identify.

23:05.676 --> 23:08.012
I don't understand.

23:08.054 --> 23:09.847
All of that from a cut
in his palm?

23:09.889 --> 23:12.600
-There was no sickness
when you arrived?
-No.

23:12.642 --> 23:15.478
God, his eyes.

23:15.520 --> 23:17.355
KRISTOFF: The blood is not
the worst of it.

23:17.396 --> 23:19.357
JAN:
You don't understand.

23:19.398 --> 23:22.902
This would be like
denying him food, air.

23:22.944 --> 23:26.489
KRISTOFF:
Your brother rots

23:26.531 --> 23:28.991
from the outside in.

23:29.033 --> 23:31.077
I am sure there
must be something.

23:31.119 --> 23:35.832
What afflicts your brother
is not disease.

23:35.873 --> 23:38.334
It's the curse.

23:42.046 --> 23:44.173
-Do you want
to save your brother?
-Of course I do.

23:44.215 --> 23:47.885
-Because he's your livelihood?
-Because I love him.

23:47.927 --> 23:50.513
Then break the curse.

23:50.555 --> 23:52.557
I-I don't believe in the curse.

23:52.598 --> 23:56.018
The clock, it does not
take any interest

23:56.060 --> 23:57.728
in what you believe.

23:57.770 --> 24:01.357
Your brother has,
at most, days to live.

24:01.399 --> 24:02.692
Fix it.

24:02.733 --> 24:06.487
Make the Orloj turn again.

24:06.529 --> 24:10.908
Break the curse
while some time remains.

24:10.950 --> 24:13.703
KRISTOFF:
Beauty, they say,

24:13.744 --> 24:15.705
is in the eye of the beholder.

24:15.746 --> 24:17.331
It can inspire many things.

24:17.373 --> 24:21.836
Oftentimes, jealousy and greed.

24:21.878 --> 24:25.298
The masters of the city didn't
want the splendor of the Orloj

24:25.339 --> 24:28.426
to be given
to any other cities.

24:28.467 --> 24:30.261
They threatened Master Hanus

24:30.303 --> 24:32.430
to never replicate it,

24:32.471 --> 24:35.474
but he refused.

24:35.516 --> 24:37.101
The soldiers,

24:37.143 --> 24:39.353
like they often do
when carrying out orders

24:39.395 --> 24:42.732
from those in charge,
showed no mercy.

24:45.610 --> 24:47.612
(screaming)

24:50.156 --> 24:53.868
KRISTOFF: Master Hanus found
his way back to the clock.

24:53.910 --> 24:56.829
He uttered a curse
on the city of Prague.

24:56.871 --> 24:58.873
Terror, destruction,

24:58.915 --> 25:01.918
and to those who would dare
repair the Orloj,

25:01.959 --> 25:04.754
madness and death.

25:07.048 --> 25:09.300
Then hurled himself
into the machine,

25:09.342 --> 25:13.179
sanctifying his dark wishes
in his own blood.

25:22.730 --> 25:27.526
I was there that night,
you see.

25:31.364 --> 25:33.366
(bones crunching)

26:01.644 --> 26:03.646
♪ ♪

26:10.778 --> 26:13.239
I was just a boy then,

26:13.281 --> 26:16.701
but I saw the clock
weep with blood.

26:19.120 --> 26:22.707
And so, it seems, did he.

26:22.748 --> 26:26.919
Doctor, I have spent
the whole day in the clock

26:26.961 --> 26:29.338
trying to make sense,

26:29.380 --> 26:32.883
but I have no expertise,
no crew, no plans.

26:32.925 --> 26:34.552
And no choice.

26:36.971 --> 26:40.266
Save your brother.
Save all of us.

26:45.980 --> 26:47.732
(gears clanking)

27:01.329 --> 27:03.331
(crying)

27:18.137 --> 27:20.139
These are plans.

27:23.184 --> 27:26.604
You drew plans.

27:26.645 --> 27:30.649
Brother, you obsessive
lunatic boy.

27:38.616 --> 27:40.743
We're going to beat you!

27:40.785 --> 27:41.869
(gears clicking)

27:41.911 --> 27:43.704
Dirvick and I,

27:43.746 --> 27:46.749
we're going to fix
this damned clock,

27:46.791 --> 27:49.627
and you can take your vengeance
and your curse

27:49.668 --> 27:53.089
and your doomed futures
back to Hell!

27:55.216 --> 27:57.843
We're going to beat you.

28:03.557 --> 28:06.018
(laughing)

28:21.158 --> 28:25.079
I have plans,
but no one to help me,

28:25.121 --> 28:28.624
and I cannot do this alone.

28:28.666 --> 28:32.378
Hey. The clock is trying
to take my brother.

28:32.420 --> 28:35.339
I did not return
for your brother's sake.

28:35.381 --> 28:39.176
-Then money, triple your rate.
-Nor money.

28:39.218 --> 28:43.931
When the clock
almost took my hand...

28:43.973 --> 28:46.267
fires,

28:46.308 --> 28:49.687
deaths,

28:49.728 --> 28:51.355
burned-out buildings,

28:51.397 --> 28:54.442
metal beasts, burned-out eyes.

28:54.483 --> 28:58.320
I have seen things,
horrible things.

29:26.056 --> 29:28.267
(metallic squeaking)

29:47.036 --> 29:49.038
(grunts softly)

30:28.077 --> 30:31.539
Stay with me. Please.

30:39.755 --> 30:42.800
(flies buzzing)

30:48.055 --> 30:50.808
(chickens clucking)

30:53.060 --> 30:56.355
It's complete. Every gear.

30:56.397 --> 30:58.232
Just as your brother specified.

30:59.775 --> 31:02.945
JAN:
Beautiful.

31:02.987 --> 31:04.196
But it is not running.

31:04.238 --> 31:07.366
N-No, I-I couldn't.

31:07.408 --> 31:08.993
Not again.

31:09.034 --> 31:12.204
Please... you start it.

31:18.210 --> 31:21.797
Just, uh, t-turn the handle.

31:21.839 --> 31:24.550
And-and be careful.

31:38.022 --> 31:40.399
You are certain all is correct?

31:40.441 --> 31:42.610
Well, as certain
as I-I can be, Jan.

31:42.651 --> 31:43.986
I'm no clockmaker.

31:44.028 --> 31:45.654
Nor am I.

31:45.696 --> 31:48.115
Must've missed something, uh...

31:48.157 --> 31:51.660
Perhaps in the,
in the trigger.

31:51.702 --> 31:54.663
Here, I'll-I'll return
in the morning.

32:01.170 --> 32:03.589
Of course.
We'll start again.

32:09.511 --> 32:12.056
♪ ♪

32:16.352 --> 32:17.561
The key.

32:19.813 --> 32:22.358
The ring.

32:39.333 --> 32:41.919
(gears clicking)

32:56.058 --> 32:58.018
(chuckling)

33:03.232 --> 33:05.192
You are beaten!

33:22.459 --> 33:25.337
Dirvick.
We fixed it.

33:25.379 --> 33:29.675
We did. Together.

33:29.717 --> 33:31.343
Dirvick.

33:35.889 --> 33:37.975
Dirvick?

33:39.852 --> 33:42.980
We fixed the clock.

33:48.902 --> 33:50.571
Fix the clock,

33:50.612 --> 33:53.449
break the curse.

33:53.490 --> 33:55.492
(sobbing)

33:57.369 --> 33:59.913
For what it matters,

33:59.955 --> 34:02.916
I-I am so sorry.

34:02.958 --> 34:05.127
Sorry?

34:08.547 --> 34:13.093
You told me...

34:13.135 --> 34:15.929
fixing the clock would save him,

34:15.971 --> 34:17.723
reverse the disease.

34:17.765 --> 34:20.851
I knew there was little hope
for your brother,

34:20.893 --> 34:22.853
but there was hope for us.

34:22.895 --> 34:28.192
Hope to fix my father's sins.

34:28.233 --> 34:31.695
Hope to ease the suffering

34:31.737 --> 34:34.698
of the people of Prague.

34:34.740 --> 34:36.658
-But you lied.
-You lied

34:36.700 --> 34:37.993
when you invented your names.

34:38.035 --> 34:41.163
We-we do lie sometimes.
I-I lied.

34:41.205 --> 34:44.458
My father was one of the
soldiers who created the curse.

34:47.336 --> 34:49.421
(screaming)

34:49.463 --> 34:53.592
His actions have tortured the
people of the city ever since.

34:53.634 --> 34:59.431
But you and your brother--
Turks, even-- saved us.

34:59.473 --> 35:02.976
I know your brother had
a tragic, tragic death,

35:03.018 --> 35:08.023
but his life saved us.

35:08.065 --> 35:12.027
You murdered my brother.

35:12.069 --> 35:13.821
He wanted to help.
He wanted to stay.

35:13.862 --> 35:16.782
To pay for the sins
of your father?

35:16.824 --> 35:20.035
I did it for the city of Prague.

35:20.077 --> 35:25.040
The little mother shall live.

35:25.082 --> 35:27.543
The plague shall leave us.

35:27.584 --> 35:30.671
We shall be cured.

35:30.712 --> 35:33.048
You... have cured us!

35:33.090 --> 35:34.883
Don't you see that?

35:34.925 --> 35:39.972
False hope is crueler

35:40.013 --> 35:42.808
than no hope.

35:51.608 --> 35:53.360
(sniffles)

36:12.170 --> 36:14.172
(creaking, ticking)

36:34.234 --> 36:36.153
Aah!

36:51.043 --> 36:54.755
Yes. Yes, of course.

37:19.112 --> 37:22.324
I'm so sorry.

37:32.167 --> 37:34.169
(Jan screaming)

37:41.218 --> 37:42.970
(bones crunching)

37:49.893 --> 37:51.812
Jan?

38:05.617 --> 38:07.577
(gears stop)

38:07.619 --> 38:09.621
♪ ♪
